                      <td height="407" width="100%"><br>
                        <table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">What is Cheating?</font></td></tr></table><BR><table WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING="4"><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This is a great article. It deals with an important aspect of the game in a clear, reasoned way. I suppose I must get my 2 cents in:<br>
If a card says &quot;do&quot; something or increases the cost to do something, then that becomes part of the rules of the game. There is no valid excuse for deliberately failing to do it. I think that it is important to have the skill to monitor and enforce the cards you deploy because you can not depend on your opponent to do it. It is not your responsibility in a moral sense. Both players should follow the rules and if there is a card on the table that says &quot;add 2 to the deploy cost of card x,&quot; then failing to add 2 is no different than trying to deploy Lord Vader for 4 force. However, there are often so many cards in play that it is difficult for a player to keep track. So it is reasonable that someone could miss something. If you have a greater awareness of all the forces in play at any given time, you have an advantage. There is no need to heighten the advantage by &quot;forgetting&quot; to do things.<br>
I think many players have succumbed to temptation on occasion. That is not good but it is forgivable. Sometimes the competetive instinct gets the better of a person. What I find less palatable is making the decision to ignore the rules before the game even starts.<br>
Anyway, great article on an important topic. Thanks.   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=29">rayc</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">cheaters suck. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=1712">GG BLADE</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Let&#146;s hope all of those cheating jerks out there listen to this article. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=4659">Prince Xizor</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Good article. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=4459">Adrenaline</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Steve,  the game I played against you in game 6 of Y4 regional this past year still ranks as one of the best games I&#146;ve ever played.  As for the article, it was very well thought out and terribly lucid(two qualities often lacking in articles around this place).  I agree with many of your points, and I do find it to be a very fine line to tread.  I often find myself reminding my opponent about his Visage when it hurts him as much as me.  This is an issue that is going to be even more poigniant as the 