<br>
My next quote, &quot;This article changed an aspect of how I think about the game mechanics (should always be something dealing with the larger picture, not a specific card)&quot;  This article has everything to do with that quote.  Especially the &quot;larger picture&quot; part.  I agree with your points about my card/my responsibility.  More importantly, it helps to point out to your opponent (especially if that person is a beginner), &quot;You forgot to force drain here.&quot;  But only do it once, because after that, it&#146;s their fault if they forget.  This also applies to other beginner&#146;s mistakes that we all make (too numerous to mention).<br>
<br>
Most of all, the SW:CCG field has many members, ranging from very young to adulthood.  It is important to remember the basics of a game: it&#146;s all for fun, nothing more.  Sure, it&#146;s no fun to lose a tournament, but it&#146;s meant to be a learning experience.  How did I lose?  How could my deck be better?  What was the deciding factor of my defeat?  These things keep us coming back for more. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=3301">BreakWindu71</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Steve you took a lot of time to write a well thought out article.  The &quot;my card ... my responsability&quot; rule is what I have always done.  Eric Olson taught me this early in the gaming days.  You need to be aware of the game at all times.  This is why SWCCG rocks.  You need to be surveying the playing field at all times.  Thanx for a great article!<br>
