Bravo 24 </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=187">Bane Slader</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">BOMB! </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=373">arebelspy</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">I enjoy reading your writing, hearing your views and marvelling at your ability to use the shift key. With that in mind, here are my comments and thoughts. Firstly, don&#146;t take responsibility for an opponent&#146;s card. Even if it&#146;s on your side of the table. That applies unless you&#146;re playing a newbie in a local, in which case remind them to remind you (this helps to teach them the game, which is important for us all - you should be winning this game anyway).  The other time you should remember is during friendlies and playtesting, when it&#146;s important to know the strength of your deck when the pressure is really on. <BR> <BR> However, I&#146;d take this rule further at the top level. If you&#146;re playing with the rest of the big boys then provided you aren&#146;t (a) making a complete arse of yourself (you need to judge this or else the TD will), or (b) breaking the fundamental rules of the game, then it&#146;s perfectly acceptable to make the opponent remind you every time for YOUR visage, YOUR Bring Him Before Me or the loss of 1 force to a 3 point drain with HB. <BR> <BR> Star Wars is played out between two minds and the luck factor is shifting increasingly from card draws and destiny (which can detract from every player&#146;s performance no matter what their skill) to deck matchups. Once you&#146;re paired and you&#146;re playing for the big prize, you should punish your opponent for every mistake he makes. Whether that&#146;s taking advantage of his omission to leave a force for barrier, successfully bluffing a monnok to stop him drawing the winning cards or just moving Leia away when she&#146;s been Beaten and he didn&#146;t stop you (controversial that one...I don&#146;t know). <BR> <BR> Here&#146;s an example from worlds this year. Dom Gaudreault made a crucial move in DBay transit of the Emperor to a location I occupied. I noticed on his next turn this was not allowed. I hadn&#146;t been concentrating on his moves, it was too late to rectify it and he won the game, fair and square. Whether he did that intentionally or not is moot. I&#146;m not going to bear any malice. Text like that and battle plan is something you might take note of at the bottom, but try to ignore at the top. On the reverse side, dropping cards onto your reserve deck, retreiving cards without cause, overactivation, whatever...that sort of stuff is out of line. Card text is one thing, playing by the rules is quite another. <BR> <BR> There are some ideas anyway, a bit jumbled I know. If you want to talk about this more, dmail. SW:CCG play theories and ideas are a favourite topic of mine. Cheers. Alex Tennet. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=327">Greedo</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="90%"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">best article on decktech......and i agree with everything you said </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD>&nbsp;</TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="/swccg/membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=931">Crusher</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="RIGHT" WIDTH="10%"><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VA