<br>
You get 5 stars for an exhaustive and honest approach to an<br>
important subject, but if everyone was to follow your first<br>
two guidelines, the game would fall into a sorry state. By<br>
saying so firmly, &quot;You be responsible for your cards, and<br>
I&#146;ll be responsible for mine,&quot; you may find a fair way of<br>
dealing with a situation--but what situation? You encourage<br>
the contest over the game, meaning it becomes all about<br>
winning--not fun. Your first two guidelines seem to permit<br>
people to intentionally &quot;forget&quot; cards, and that&#146;s just<br>
wrong. Even if there&#146;s no fair way to judge it. It&#146;s just a<br>
sickening habit--intentionally forgetting. I go to tournies<br>
for fun. So do many people. And when I&#146;ve played people who<br>
intentionally &quot;forget,&quot; it ruins an hour of my life. That&#146;s<br>
an hour wasted. That&#146;s not the experience I desire from<br>
cards. If winning means that much to you, you&#146;ve lost focus<br>
about what the game is. It&#146;s no longer a game; it&#146;s the<br>
flexing of your ego. What&#146;s better? Play as fair and<br>
honorably as possible. Expect your opponent to play the<br>
same. The only &quot;forgotten&quot; cards that are okay are the ones<br>
that are honestly forgotten. Really, when it comes down to<br>
it, wouldn&#146;t any sporting player rather feel the<br>
satisfaction of winning a game through deck design, tactics<br>
and luck rather than by knowing &quot;I bought myself 5 force by<br>
intentionally &#146;forgetting&#146;?&quot; Think about that.<br>
<br>
